<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910222-0071</DOCNO><DOCID>910222-0071.</DOCID><HL>   Lufthansa Considers   Shorter Work Shifts   As Bookings Decline   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>02/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3C</SO><CO>   G.LHA</CO><IN>AIRLINES (AIR)</IN><LP>   FRANKFURT, Germany -- Lufthansa German Airlines, citing adrop in bookings due to the war in the Persian Gulf, isstudying the possibility of introducing short shifts foreligible staff starting March 1.   The idea of shortened shifts is only being studied at themoment and a final decision, along with the extent of such aprogram if it takes place, will be announced Tuesday, aspokesman said.</LP><TEXT>   The airline has 47,000 workers, although not all -- suchas airline safety workers -- are eligible for shortenedshifts.   Under Germany's short-shift program, an employer canreduce a workers' hours and the Federal Labor Office will paya portion of the lost wages.   Last month, the flagship German airline announced thatbookings had plunged more than a third since the Jan. 17outbreak of the war. This month, the company said its 1990profits dropped to a break-even position.   The company said it is in discussions with theBetriebsrat, or in-house workers' council, on the possibilityof short shifts.   Bookings have begun to increase, the company said, butnevertheless are &quot;clearly below&quot; last year's levels for thisperiod. The company didn't provide any numbers.   The increases were linked to the general normalization ofoperations at airports and the lifting of travel restrictionsby many large corporations.</TEXT></DOC>